<p><b>Afrihili</b> (<i>Ni Afrihili Oluga</i> 'the Afrihili language') is a <a href="/wiki/Constructed_language" title="Constructed language">constructed language</a> designed in 1970 by K. A. Kumi Attobrah (Kumi Atɔbra) to be used as a <a href="/wiki/Lingua_franca" title="Lingua franca">lingua franca</a> in all of <a href="/wiki/Africa" title="Africa">Africa</a>. The name of the language is a combination of <i>Africa</i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Swahili_language" title="Swahili language">Swahili</a></i>. The author, a native of <a href="/w/index.php?title=Akrokerri&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Akrokerri (page does not exist)">Akrokerri</a> (Akrokɛri) in <a href="/wiki/Ghana" title="Ghana">Ghana</a>, originally conceived of the idea in 1967 while on a sea voyage from <a href="/wiki/Dover" title="Dover">Dover</a> to <a href="/wiki/Calais" title="Calais">Calais</a>. His intention was that "it would promote unity and understanding among the different peoples of the continent, reduce costs in printing due to translations and promote trade". It is meant to be easy for Africans to learn.</p>
